# üéØ Executive Summary & Business Context

This ticket outlines the development of a React TypeScript component based on the Bootstrap Card design. The business impact is to provide a reusable and visually consistent content container across various applications. The user value proposition is a clear and organized presentation of information. Strategic alignment is achieved by adhering to the design system and using standard UI elements.

## üè¢ Business Requirements & User Context

In a general industry business model, content cards are used to display summaries or previews of information, linking to more detailed views. User personas might include marketing professionals showcasing product features or customer support representatives providing knowledge base articles. The business model alignment involves enhancing user engagement and conversion rates by presenting information in a visually appealing and easily digestible manner.

## üë§ User Experience Strategy

The cognitive load needs to be optimized by ensuring the information within the card is well-structured and concise. The user journey integration involves placing the card in relevant contexts, such as search results, product listings, or dashboard overviews. The conversion goals can be achieved by including clear call-to-action buttons within the card, driving users to take specific actions.

## üìã Technical Analysis & Architecture

The implementation strategy for React TypeScript involves creating a reusable component that accepts various props for content, styling, and actions. The complexity is assessed as medium-high due to the need for responsive design and potential integration with external data sources. The architecture pattern is a simple component with prop-based rendering. This can be a functional component using hooks for any internal state management.

## üé® Design System Implementation

The component should adhere to the established design system for brand alignment. Design tokens should be used for colors (#f7fafa and #212629), typography (system-ui, 16px), and spacing (4px, 8px, 16px, 24px, 32px). The card should be responsive, adapting to different screen sizes using media queries or a grid system. The font sizes and weights should ensure readability and hierarchy.

## ‚úÖ Intelligence-Driven Acceptance Criteria

*   The component renders correctly with different content types (text, images, links).
*   The component is responsive and adapts to different screen sizes.
*   The component is accessible, with appropriate ARIA attributes and keyboard navigation.
*   The component's performance is optimized, with lazy loading of images if necessary.
*   The component integrates seamlessly into the existing design system.
*   The card displays content correctly when the title, subtitle, and body are all present.
*   The card displays content correctly when some of the fields like subtitle are missing.
*   The card should support a header and footer slot for custom content.
*   The card should have optional support for displaying an image.

## üîß Development Strategy & Implementation

*   Code architecture: Create a React TypeScript component with well-defined props.
*   Time estimates: 24 hours
*   Risk mitigation: Ensure cross-browser compatibility and thorough testing.
*   Testing strategy: Unit tests, integration tests, and visual regression tests.
*   Component File: `src/components/BootstrapCard/BootstrapCard.tsx`
*   Implement the base Bootstrap Card structure using semantic HTML elements like `<article>` or `<div>`.
*   Define a TypeScript interface for the component's props, including title, subtitle, body, image URL, and any action buttons.
*   Use the detected colors #f7fafa (light background) and #212629 (dark text/secondary background).
*   Implement responsive typography using CSS variables and media queries.
*   Add accessibility features like `aria-label` and proper heading hierarchy.
*   Implement optional image loading using `<img>` tag with appropriate `alt` text and lazy loading if needed.
*   Consider using `React.forwardRef` for advanced use cases requiring DOM access.
*   Implement conditional rendering to handle cases where title, subtitle or body are not provided.
*   Add storybook support for different use cases of the card
*   Implement basic CSS-in-JS styling based on the design system, using styled-components or emotion.

```typescript
import React from 'react';
import styled from 'styled-components';

interface BootstrapCardProps {
  title: string;
  subtitle?: string;
  body: string;
  imageUrl?: string;
  className?: string;
}

const StyledBootstrapCard = styled.article`
  background-color: #f7fafa;
  color: #212629;
  font-family: system-ui;
  border: 1px solid #ddd;
  border-radius: 0.25rem;
  padding: 16px;
  margin-bottom: 16px;

  h5 {
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }

  h6 {
    font-size: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 16px;
    color: #6c757d;
  }

  p {
    font-size: 16px;
  }

  img {
    max-width: 100%;
    height: auto;
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }
`;

const BootstrapCard: React.FC<BootstrapCardProps> = ({ title, subtitle, body, imageUrl, className }) => {
  return (
    <StyledBootstrapCard className={className}>
      {imageUrl && <img src={imageUrl} alt={title} />}
      <h5>{title}</h5>
      {subtitle && <h6>{subtitle}</h6>}
      <p>{body}</p>
    </StyledBootstrapCard>
  );
};

export default BootstrapCard;
```

